  <H1>Hodgkin-Huxley Model: Biophysical Foundation</H1>

  <Body>The Hodgkin-Huxley (HH) model represents one of the most significant achievements in computational neuroscience—a quantitative framework that explains how voltage-gated ion channels generate action potentials through the precise orchestration of sodium activation, sodium inactivation, and potassium activation. Developed by Alan Hodgkin and Andrew Huxley in 1952 based on their voltage-clamp experiments on the giant squid axon, this model earned them the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1963 and remains foundational to all modern neuronal modeling.</Body>

  <Body>In the previous lesson on the Integrate-and-Fire model, we treated threshold as an abstract parameter. The Hodgkin-Huxley model provides a mechanistic explanation for threshold behavior through the dynamics of voltage-gated ion channels. Understanding these dynamics is essential for modeling realistic neuronal behavior and interpreting experimental data.</Body>

  <H2>Ionic Current Formulation</H2>

  <Body>The foundation of the HH model rests on Ohm's law applied to ionic currents across the membrane. Each ionic current is proportional to both a conductance (which may be voltage-dependent) and the driving force—the difference between the membrane potential V and the reversal potential E for that ion species:</Body>

  <Code lang="plaintext">
I_ion = g_ion × (V - E_ion)
  </Code>

  <Body>The reversal potential (also called equilibrium potential) for each ion is determined by the Nernst equation and reflects the concentration gradient across the membrane. For a typical mammalian neuron at 37°C:</Body>

  <Body>• E_Na ≈ +55 mV (sodium tends to flow inward, depolarizing the cell)</Body>
  <Body>• E_K ≈ -77 mV (potassium tends to flow outward, hyperpolarizing the cell)</Body>
  <Body>• E_L ≈ -65 mV (leak current, primarily chloride)</Body>

  <FlashCard id="fc1">
    <Front>What is the reversal potential (equilibrium potential) and what determines its value?</Front>
    <Back>The reversal potential is the membrane voltage at which the electrical and concentration gradients for an ion species are balanced, resulting in zero net current for that ion. Its value is determined by the Nernst equation based on the concentration gradient of the ion across the membrane.</Back>
  </FlashCard>

  <FlashCard id="fc2">
    <Front>Why does sodium have a positive reversal potential (~+55 mV) while potassium has a negative one (~-77 mV)?</Front>
    <Back>Sodium is concentrated outside the cell (high [Na⁺]_out / [Na⁺]_in ratio), so its equilibrium requires a positive interior to oppose inward diffusion. Potassium is concentrated inside (high [K⁺]_in / [K⁺]_out ratio), so its equilibrium requires a negative interior to oppose outward diffusion. These concentration gradients are maintained by the Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase pump.</Back>
  </FlashCard>

  <H2>The Complete Hodgkin-Huxley Equation</H2>

  <Body>The HH model describes the membrane potential dynamics through a differential equation that accounts for capacitive current and three ionic currents—sodium (Na), potassium (K), and leak (L):</Body>

  <Code lang="plaintext">
C_m × dV/dt = -g_Na × m³ × h × (V - E_Na) - g_K × n⁴ × (V - E_K) - g_L × (V - E_L) + I_ext
  </Code>

  <Body>Here, C_m is the membrane capacitance (typically ~1 μF/cm²), g_Na, g_K, and g_L are maximal conductances, and I_ext represents externally applied current. The variables m, h, and n are dimensionless gating variables (ranging from 0 to 1) that describe the state of voltage-gated ion channels.</Body>

  <Body>The key insight is that sodium and potassium conductances are not fixed but depend on voltage through the gating variables:</Body>

  <Body>• Sodium conductance: g_Na(V,t) = ḡ_Na × m³ × h</Body>
  <Body>• Potassium conductance: g_K(V,t) = ḡ_K × n⁴</Body>
  <Body>• Leak conductance: g_L (constant, voltage-independent)</Body>

  <H2>Gating Variable Kinetics</H2>

  <Body>Each gating variable follows first-order kinetics described by voltage-dependent rate constants α(V) and β(V):</Body>

  <Code lang="plaintext">
dm/dt = α_m(V) × (1 - m) - β_m(V) × m
dh/dt = α_h(V) × (1 - h) - β_h(V) × h
dn/dt = α_n(V) × (1 - n) - β_n(V) × n
  </Code>

  <Body>These equations can be rewritten in terms of the steady-state activation x_∞(V) and time constant τ_x(V):</Body>

  <Code lang="plaintext">
dx/dt = (x_∞(V) - x) / τ_x(V)

where:
x_∞(V) = α_x(V) / (α_x(V) + β_x(V))
τ_x(V) = 1 / (α_x(V) + β_x(V))
  </Code>

  <Body>This formulation makes clear that each gating variable relaxes exponentially toward its steady-state value with a characteristic time constant that depends on voltage.</Body>

  <FlashCard id="fc3">
    <Front>What is the physical interpretation of the gating variable m in the HH model?</Front>
    <Back>The variable m represents the probability that a sodium channel activation gate is open. Since HH assumed three independent activation gates per channel (based on fitting experimental data), the probability that all three are open is m³. This m variable activates rapidly upon depolarization, opening the sodium channels.</Back>
  </FlashCard>

  <FlashCard id="fc4">
    <Front>What distinguishes the h gating variable from m and n?</Front>
    <Back>The h variable represents sodium channel inactivation, not activation. Unlike m and n which increase with depolarization (opening channels), h decreases with depolarization (closing/inactivating sodium channels). Inactivation via h is also slower than activation via m, creating the transient nature of sodium current during an action potential.</Back>
  </FlashCard>

  <H2>Voltage-Dependent Rate Functions</H2>

  <Body>Hodgkin and Huxley derived empirical expressions for the rate functions from their voltage-clamp experiments on squid giant axon at 6.3°C. The original formulations (with V measured relative to resting potential) are:</Body>

  <Code lang="python">
import numpy as np

def alpha_m(V):
    """Sodium activation rate (ms⁻¹)"""
    return 0.1 * (25 - V) / (np.exp((25 - V) / 10) - 1)

def beta_m(V):
    """Sodium activation rate (ms⁻¹)"""
    return 4 * np.exp(-V / 18)

def alpha_h(V):
    """Sodium inactivation rate (ms⁻¹)"""
    return 0.07 * np.exp(-V / 20)

def beta_h(V):
    """Sodium inactivation rate (ms⁻¹)"""
    return 1 / (np.exp((30 - V) / 10) + 1)

def alpha_n(V):
    """Potassium activation rate (ms⁻¹)"""
    return 0.01 * (10 - V) / (np.exp((10 - V) / 10) - 1)

def beta_n(V):
    """Potassium activation rate (ms⁻¹)"""
    return 0.125 * np.exp(-V / 80)
  </Code>

  <Body>Note: These formulations have potential numerical issues when the denominator approaches zero. Modern implementations handle these singularities using L'Hôpital's rule or by checking for values near the singularity.</Body>

  <FlashCard id="fc5">
    <Front>Why are the rate functions α(V) and β(V) empirically fitted rather than derived from first principles?</Front>
    <Back>Hodgkin and Huxley used voltage-clamp experiments to measure ionic currents at different fixed voltages. They fitted the observed kinetics with mathematical functions that accurately reproduced the data. At the time (1952), the molecular structure of ion channels was unknown—their molecular basis wasn't established until decades later with cloning and crystallography studies.</Back>
  </FlashCard>

  <H2>Understanding the Gating Variables</H2>

  <H3>Sodium Channel: m (Activation) and h (Inactivation)</H3>

  <Body>The sodium channel has two types of gates that govern its behavior:</Body>

  <Body>1. Activation gates (m): Three independent gates that open rapidly upon depolarization. The probability of all three being open is m³, giving the characteristic steep voltage dependence of sodium activation.</Body>

  <Body>2. Inactivation gate (h): One gate that closes slowly during sustained depolarization. This creates the transient nature of sodium current—channels open quickly but then inactivate even if voltage remains depolarized.</Body>

  <Body>At rest (~−65 mV): m ≈ 0.05 (mostly closed), h ≈ 0.60 (mostly not inactivated)</Body>
  <Body>During depolarization: m increases rapidly (channels activate), h decreases slowly (channels inactivate)</Body>

  <H3>Potassium Channel: n (Activation)</H3>

  <Body>The potassium channel is simpler, with four independent activation gates (n⁴). Key features:</Body>

  <Body>• Activates with depolarization (like m)</Body>
  <Body>• Slower kinetics than sodium activation—this delay is crucial for repolarization</Body>
  <Body>• No inactivation in the classical HH model (though some K⁺ channels do inactivate)</Body>

  <Body>At rest: n ≈ 0.32 (some channels open, contributing to resting conductance)</Body>
  <Body>During depolarization: n increases slowly, reaching peak after sodium current has peaked</Body>

  <FlashCard id="fc6">
    <Front>Why do sodium channels have both activation (m) AND inactivation (h) while potassium channels only have activation (n)?</Front>
    <Back>Sodium channels need both gates to produce the transient inward current required for rapid depolarization followed by automatic termination. The fast activation (m) opens channels, while slow inactivation (h) closes them regardless of continued depolarization. Potassium channels' delayed activation alone suffices for repolarization—they open after the sodium current and don't need to inactivate because the cell naturally hyperpolarizes.</Back>
  </FlashCard>

  <H2>Action Potential Phases</H2>

  <Body>The interplay of sodium and potassium channel dynamics produces the characteristic action potential waveform with distinct phases:</Body>

  <Body>1. Resting state: V ≈ −65 mV, m low, h high, n moderate. The leak current and partial K⁺ conductance maintain resting potential.</Body>

  <Body>2. Depolarization (rising phase): Stimulus causes initial depolarization → m increases rapidly → Na⁺ channels open → inward I_Na depolarizes membrane further (positive feedback) → V rapidly approaches E_Na.</Body>

  <Body>3. Repolarization (falling phase): h decreases (Na⁺ inactivation) → I_Na decreases. Simultaneously, n increases (K⁺ activation) → I_K increases → outward current repolarizes membrane → V returns toward rest.</Body>

  <Body>4. Hyperpolarization (undershoot): Because K⁺ channel deactivation is slow, I_K remains elevated even as V passes through rest → V undershoots to below resting potential (closer to E_K).</Body>

  <Body>5. Recovery: n slowly decreases (K⁺ deactivation), h slowly increases (Na⁺ recovery from inactivation) → membrane returns to resting state.</Body>

