  <H2>Understanding Threshold Mechanistically</H2>

  <Body>Unlike the Integrate-and-Fire model where threshold is a fixed parameter, the HH model provides a mechanistic explanation for threshold behavior:</Body>

  <Body>The effective threshold is the voltage at which the positive feedback from sodium current overcomes the negative feedback from potassium and leak currents. Mathematically, this occurs when:</Body>

  <Code lang="plaintext">
dI_Na/dV &gt; dI_K/dV + dI_L/dV

The sodium current's voltage dependence (through m³h) creates a regenerative process:
depolarization → increased m → increased I_Na → further depolarization
  </Code>

  <Body>This explains several observations:</Body>
  <Body>• Threshold is not fixed but depends on the rate of depolarization (accommodation)</Body>
  <Body>• Threshold increases during the relative refractory period (reduced h, elevated n)</Body>
  <Body>• Different stimulation protocols can produce different apparent thresholds</Body>

  <H2>Ionic Current Decomposition</H2>

  <Body>Analyzing the individual ionic currents during an action potential reveals the precise timing and magnitude of each contribution:</Body>

  <Body>1. At rest: Small outward I_K and I_L balance, I_Na negligible (low m)</Body>
  <Body>2. Rising phase: Large inward I_Na (m rapidly increases, h still high), I_K slowly increasing</Body>
  <Body>3. Peak: I_Na begins decreasing (h dropping), I_K continuing to increase</Body>
  <Body>4. Falling phase: I_Na minimal (h ≈ 0), I_K maximal, net outward current</Body>
  <Body>5. Undershoot: I_Na still inactivated, I_K elevated, driving V toward E_K</Body>
  <Body>6. Recovery: Both currents return toward resting values</Body>

