  <H2>Experimental Connections</H2>

  <Body>The HH model was derived from and validated against specific experimental preparations and techniques:</Body>

  <Body>Voltage clamp experiments: By holding membrane potential constant, Hodgkin and Huxley isolated ionic currents and determined their voltage dependence. This technique remains essential for characterizing channel properties.</Body>

  <Body>Pharmacological dissection: Tetrodotoxin (TTX) blocks sodium channels; tetraethylammonium (TEA) blocks potassium channels. These tools allow experimental separation of current components.</Body>

  <Body>The squid giant axon: Its large diameter (~500 μm) made it ideal for early electrophysiology. While parameter values differ for mammalian neurons, the fundamental mechanisms are conserved.</Body>

  <FlashCard id="fc7">
    <Front>What is the voltage clamp technique and why was it essential for developing the HH model?</Front>
    <Back>Voltage clamp uses electronic feedback to hold membrane potential at a commanded value despite ionic currents. This allowed Hodgkin and Huxley to measure ionic currents at fixed voltages, separating the current-voltage relationship from the time-dependent dynamics. They could then determine how conductances depend on voltage and time—information impossible to extract from normal action potential recordings where voltage changes continuously.</Back>
  </FlashCard>

  <H2>Summary: Key Equations</H2>

  <Body>The complete HH model consists of four coupled differential equations:</Body>

  <Code lang="plaintext">
Membrane potential:
C_m × dV/dt = -g_Na × m³h × (V - E_Na) - g_K × n⁴ × (V - E_K) - g_L × (V - E_L) + I_ext

Gating variables:
dm/dt = α_m(V)(1-m) - β_m(V)m     [sodium activation, fast]
dh/dt = α_h(V)(1-h) - β_h(V)h     [sodium inactivation, slow]
dn/dt = α_n(V)(1-n) - β_n(V)n     [potassium activation, slow]

Standard parameter values (squid axon, 6.3°C):
C_m = 1 μF/cm², g_Na = 120 mS/cm², g_K = 36 mS/cm², g_L = 0.3 mS/cm²
E_Na = 50 mV, E_K = -77 mV, E_L = -54.4 mV
  </Code>

